<font color="#FF0000">DID VIETNAM EVER REALLY END?</font><br>
<tt>Tue Mar 11 14:16:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I just finished spending probably 5 hours reading all of<br>
the nearly 200 posts on this thread.  It has been quite<br>
fascinating, almost like having the opportunity to step<br>
back into the Vietnam era.  First and foremost, I have<br>
a great feeling of compassion for all of you who endured<br>
that insane era, both protestors and vets alike.  Especially for the vets living and dead who have made<br>
ultimate sacrifices out of noble intentions, only later<br>
to be told that it was all a big mistake and for nothing.<br><br>
We can all agree that whatever the causes and reasons of<br>
the Vietnam War, it was an incredible human tragedy and<br>
I think there is no one who would not erase it if they<br>
could.  But your dialouge is so valuable to those of us<br>
of later generations who have the opportunity to learn<br>
from the past and use what we have learned to make a<br>
better future for ourselves, our children, your grand-<br>
children.<br><br>
I was born in '65, so the Vietnam War is pretty much <br>
something out of the history books for me, but I am very<br>
interested in this discussion because I am very deeply<br>
troubled by war.  I am most impressed with the posts<br>
of Jeffrey Winkler, who posseses an incredible encylopedic<br>
knowledge of the history of war, and who gives cogent,<br>
dispassionate and logical explanations about how regardless<br>
of the noble intentions of soldiers, our government sends<br>
us to war not out of such noble intentions or moral ideals<br>
but really as power plays in the giant chess game of world<br>
power and dominance.  Only this is not a game, but a meat<br>
grinder which pulverizes the lives and the spirits of<br>
untold millions.<br><br>
I was myself basically politically unconcsious until, while<br>
a student on a college campus in '90 the Persian Gulf<br>
War began.  I realize the Gulf War was not nearly as bad<br>
as the Vietnam War no matter how you slice it.  However,<br>
as a protester on campus of that war, it gave me a tiny<br>
taste of what you all went through in the '60s.<br><br>
One, I was lied to by my government, a government which<br>
hitherto I had more or less placed my faith in.  It was<br>
so clear to me that George Bush cared not one lick about<br>
the government of Kuwait, the Kurds, etc. etc.  His one<br>
and only objective was to restore American coroporate (oil)<br>
interests in the region. (BTW, did you know that George's<br>
son, Neil, at that time owned oil interests in the Gulf?).<br>
As Mr. Winkler demonstrates so much more ably than I ever<br>
could (see is pervious posts in this area), there are far, far too many counter-examples for anybody to claim that Bush was motivated by human rights, international law, or any such thing.<br><br>
Two, I had to go to bed each night during that war knowing<br>
that innocent people were being slaughtered by our military<br>
for not good enough reasons.  I believed we could have tried<br>
longer and harder to find a non-violent solution, before<br>
bombing Bahgdad back to the stone age.  I believe that in<br>
a dictatorship such as in Iraq, even the soldiers are innocent victims, since of course they don't have any choice<br>
about whether to fight in Saddam's military.<br><br>
Three, I joined the protest movement on campus.  In fact, I would say I was one of its leaders.  I lost all attention to my classes and focused entirely on doing whatever I could to stop the slaughter.  I was deeply pained and horrified that with each passing minute more bombs were falling and more people were dying, bombs that were manufactured in part by my tax dollars, and based upon lies and insufficient efforts at seeking alternatives.  During protest marches off campus,  I came to expect to be screamed at, called unamerican, receive threats of violence, even have people swerve their cars towards me like they were going to run me over, because I dared to exercise my American right to dissent.  I was so shocked and disillusioned by the hatred that came out of the woodwork.  Out of this experience, I feel I can relate to the Vietnam War protesters to some extent.  And nobody can accuse me of trying save my own ass because there was no draft and I was 26 years old at the time.  So I trust that many of the Vietnam war protesters were, like me, acting out of a passion for non-violence, not just self-interest.  But I can tell you if there had been a draft I would have been first in line to counsel 18 year olds on how to avoid it, and if they ever had sent me one, I would have had no qualms about dousing it with Bush's gasoline and 'consigning it to the flames'.  We were accused by the hawks of not supporting the troops, which was utter b.s., because what we were about was ending the violence, and bringing the troops back home.  How can we know what the motives of the majority of the Vietname War protesters were?  I have to believe that many or even most of them were like me, not against the troops but against the war.  I believe that most '60s protesters did and do not hold vets in low esteem.  I believe they hold our government to blame more than the troops.  Too bad that whatever animosity did/does exist between the vets and protesters is not directed where it ought to be: at those in  power who sit behind big desks in Washington and play God.<br><br>
I would also like to take this opportunity to point out that currently the United States is the world's leading exporter of conventional weapons, with nearly 80% of the 'market share'.  What makes this so horrific is that over 90% of the governments we are selling these weapons to are non-democratic tyrannies, most of which have been identified by our own department of state as human rights abusers.  I get this info directly from Peace Action (formerly Sane/Freeze), America's oldest and largest citizens lobby for peace and social justice.  The past four times the US has intervened abroad, U.S. troops have been killed by U.S. manufactured weapons.  It's as though Vietnam never ended, it just has splintered into all of these tiny little wars all over the planet, and what makes me so sad and outraged is that it is we who are fueling the fire with weapons.  The military budget sucks something like $400 billion a year of our tax dollars and has created a $5 trillion debt that my generation and future generations will have to pay off.  They say we need this strong military to protect us from our enemies.  But look who's selling the 'enemy' their weapons?  How long will we have to pay our own government for protection?  The Republicans will tell you that we only sell weapons to those on our side, but the bottom line is that it is immoral to sell weapons to anybody, and who is on our side today may be against us tomorrow (for example, we supported Saddam Hussein with weapons and funding in his war against Iran, then, lo and behold, suddenly we find he is no longer on our side and we have to go send our troops to clean up the mess we helped create).  I have little doubt that Mr. Winkler could provide endless additional examples.<br><br>
In conclusion, to all Vietnam Vets: thank you for your noble service and the ultimate sacrifices you made for your country and your ideals.  I am so sorry that your young idealism was exploited by a corrupt, dishonest, self-serving government seeking not primarily peace and democracy but rather control, through brute force, of world power.  I cannot fathom the horror you experienced and the pain you carry with you today, but I hope we can all come together and and direct our anger where it belongs: at the immoral, dishonest and corrupt politicians and industrialists which comprise the military-industrial complex, which to this day continues to fuel little Vietnams all over the world, through ever-increasing weapons exports and corresponding military budgets, in order to continue to justify its very existence.  All the horror you experienced in the jungles of 'nam is still being experienced all over the world today, and all too often U.S. manufactured weapons are involved.<br><br>
There was a time when, during times of peace, the military was more or less dismantled and we focused our national resources on domestic social infrastructure.  Apparently that time has passed.  Today we are continually preparing for war, and therefore maybe we should be prepared to continually be at war.<br><br>
I once read of a study which revealed that 40% of America's homeless are war veterans, primarily Vietnam War veterans.  That is a national disgrace.  Let's stop pouring this country's resources into death, destruction, and war, and for once in 50 years enjoy real peace.  The first thing we could do with a true peace dividend would be to get all the homeless vets of the streets.
<p><code>-- css@webcom.com  (Chris Schefler) </code><p>


